The paper deals with lower bounds on the complexity of first-order logic and counting logic, which are central topics in computational complexity theory (cs.CC) and logic (cs.LO). The connection to the Weisfeiler-Leman algorithm, which is a popular graph isomorphism testing algorithm, suggests that the paper may also be relevant to algorithms and complexity in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and data structures (cs.DS). Finally, the use of hardness condensation, a technique from proof complexity, suggests that the paper may also be relevant to discrete mathematics (cs.DM).
